1.What is Version Control?

Version Control is a system that tracks changes in files over time.

It allows you to:

Track who made changes

Restore previous versions

Collaborate without overwriting others’ work

Maintain project history

 Real-World Example

Imagine editing a project file:

project_v1

project_v2

final_project

final_project_latest

final_project_latest_final

This is messy and unprofessional.

Git solves this.

2️.Centralized vs Distributed Version Control
 Centralized Version Control (CVCS)

Examples:

Subversion

CVS

Characteristics:

One central server

Developers connect to that server

If server crashes → work stops

Internet required

Problem:
Single point of failure.

 Distributed Version Control (DVCS)

Example:

Git

Characteristics:

Every developer has full copy of repository

Work offline

No single point of failure

Faster operations

This is why Git dominates modern development.

3️.Why Git Was Created

Git was created in 2005 by:

Linus Torvalds

Reason:
The Linux kernel project needed a fast, distributed version control system after losing access to BitKeeper.

Requirements:

Speed

Distributed workflow

Strong branching system

Data integrity

Git was built to solve real production problems — not academic theory.

4️.How Git Actually Works (Core Concept)

This is where most beginners stay confused.

Git does NOT store files.
Git stores snapshots.

Each commit:

Takes a snapshot of entire project

Uses SHA-1 hash to uniquely identify it

Creates a commit tree

Internally Git has:

Working Directory

Staging Area (Index)

Repository (.git folder)

5️.Git File State Machine

Files in Git exist in 4 states:

Untracked

Modified

Staged

Committed

Flow:

Untracked → git add → Staged
Modified → git add → Staged
Staged → git commit → Committed

After commit:
File becomes tracked.

If you modify again → back to Modified state.

This cycle repeats.

If you don’t understand this cycle, you will misuse Git.

